The network stack and the socket.

Every networking task on Linux, reading an address, tracing a route, opening an SSH session, ultimately comes back to one thing: the socket. A socket is simply the point where a program plugs into the network, and it's identified by a small triple: an IP address, a port, and a protocol. That triple, something like ninety-three dot one-eighty-four, port four-forty-three, over TCP, uniquely names one endpoint of a conversation.

For your machine to actually send a packet, Linux needs four things lined up, and those four things are exactly the topics of this module. First, an address, sitting on a network interface, so the machine is on the network at all. Second, a route, which tells the kernel which interface and which gateway a packet should leave through. Third, a name-to-address lookup, so you can type example-dot-com instead of a raw number; that's DNS. And fourth, a rule about who is allowed to connect to you; that's the firewall.

Once all that plumbing works, the rest of the module is about using the network securely. And the star of that half is SSH, the secure shell, which is the universal remote-administration protocol. The very same ssh user-at-host command works on every Linux box, every cloud provider, and every container. So we spend real time on SSH from end to end: making the connection and verifying host keys, authenticating with keys instead of passwords, the client config file and the agent, the sshd server on the other side, and transferring files with scp and rsync.

We'll walk it all in order. A TCP/IP refresher; interfaces and getting an IP address; routing; DNS; then SSH from both ends; and finally firewalls, plus a layered troubleshooting drill for when the network simply "isn't working." One note on tools throughout: the modern commands are ip, for addresses and routes, and ss, for sockets. If you see ifconfig or netstat in an old tutorial, those are deprecated; use ip and ss instead.
